subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
The male of 

Pararhagadochir castaneus


sp. nov.

resembles those of 

P. minuta

by the small-sized body size (
7 mm
), but can be readily distinguished from the latter in having longer forewings (
6.5 mm
), lacking white bands between pro- and mesothorax (
Fig. 1
), submentum inflexed and strongly sclerotized (
Figs. 3, 4
), outer tip of 10Lp with both sclerotized and membranous areas (
Figs. 11, 12
) and Cu vein unforked (
Figs. 5, 7
).

Head capsule slightly elongate-oval, dark chestnut-brown (
Fig. 2
). Eyes black, medium-sized; separated by two eye-widths (
Fig. 2
). Antennal segments uniformly chestnut-brown, with the left antenna missing segments past the 16th and the right antenna missing segments past the 12th (left 16-x/ right 12-x). Mouthparts uniformly chestnutbrown. Submentum dark brown (
Figs. 3–4
).

Thorax and abdomen uniformly chestnut-brown (
Fig. 1
). All legs entirely brown. Medial bladder close to the apex (
Fig. 8
).

Second cercal segments slightly longer than first (
Figs. 9–11
). Hp well developed, starting in the middle of H (
Fig. 9
). LPPT sclerotized, with curved and strongly sclerotized apex (
Fig. 9
). Distal process of LC1 quadrangular (
Figs. 9–11
). Caudal margin of 10L concave (
Fig. 11
). 10Lp broad basally then tapered terminally with inner and outer tips (
Fig. 11
). Tips of 10Lp subequal (
Figs. 11, 12
). Hook-like inner tip of 10Lp strongly sclerotized (
Figs. 11, 12
). Outer tip of 10Lp with both sclerotized and membranous areas (
Figs. 11, 12
). 10Rp1 long, broad, gradually narrowing with a short and strongly sclerotized talon.
